               <desc type="site-data">
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000024c-1">Located the southwest of Ji County 薊州, Tianjin Municipality 天津市, the White Pagoda (Baita 白塔) is also known as the Dule si ta 獨樂寺塔 (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 83).</p>
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000024c-2">Although the exact construction date of the White Pagoda is unknown, in his 1930s report, Liang Sicheng 梁思成 believed the original construction should date to the <term ref="/keyword/k000047">Liao</term> dynasty (916-1125) (Liang 1932, 94). Because pagodas (<p ref="/keyword/k000060">ta 塔</p>) during the <term ref="keyword/k000082">Tang</term> dynasty (618-907) commonly had a square ground plans, the octagonal-shape ground plan suggests White Pagoda was originally constructed after that time, likely in the tenth century (Liang 1932, 95).</p>
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000024c-3">The White Pagoda aligns with the central north-south axis that extends from <term ref="/place/000024c">the Guanyin Pavilion (Guanyin ge 觀音閣)</term> at <placeName ref="/place/000024">Dule Monastery (Dule si 獨樂寺)</placeName>. It is located 380 meters south of the monastery (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 83). Thus, Liang Sicheng suggested that the construction of the White Pagoda followed the construction of the Dule Monastery and the White Pagoda may have originally been part of this larger complex (Liang 1932, 93). Nancy Steinhardt also agrees on that the White Pagoda must be interpreted as an extension of <term ref="/place/000024">Dule Monastery</term> (Steinhardt 1997, 53). Standing at the third floor of its <term ref="/place/000024c">Guanyin Pavilion</term>, one can easily see the White Pagoda directly to its south (Steinhardt 1997, 53).</p> 
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000024c-4">The White Pagoda is 30.6 meters high (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 112). The foundation is made of granite (Liang 1932, 95). It was damaged in the Tangshan earthquake 唐山大地震 in 1976 and it was rebuilt in the spring 1983 (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 119). During the repair in 1983, another pagoda dating to the <term>Liao</term> dynasty was found within the ca. 60-100 cm thick exterior brick layer 包磚層 (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 83). The enclosed pagoda consists of a waisted monumental Sumeru base 束腰須彌座, a pavilion-shaped octagonal double-eaves body 八角重檐亭式塔身, and a stupa 窣堵波 (覆鉢) (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 85). The exterior of the pagoda is made of brick carved with dougong-shaped designs, floral patterns and mythical animals (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 119).</p> 
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000024c-5">The pagoda is solid brick within which were found two vertically aligned crypts. A short finial extends from the ceiling of the upper crypt (Lin 2016, 112). Archeologists found a two-layer stone reliquary in the inner pagoda which was engraved on three sides (Steinhardt 1997, 55) with the names of Han Zhibai 韓知白, Qinjian 秦鑒 and the monk Sixiao 思孝, as well as documentation of donations of Buddhist relics. Steinhardt suggests these remains were interred here so they could be protected by the watchful eye of the Guanyin in Dule Monastery (Steinhardt 1997, 55).</p> 
                  <!--<p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000024c-1">In front of the White Pagoda is the Guanyin Monastery 觀音寺, commonly known as Baita Monastery 白塔寺 because of the White Pagoda Baita 白塔 that is housed in the monastery. According to Chongxiu yuyangjun ta ji《重修漁陽郡塔記》, the monastery was constructed during the Jiajing 嘉靖 reign period of the <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming dynasty</term> 明代 (Tianjin lishi bowuguan kaogudui 1989, 83).</p>  
                  
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000024c-5">Architectural historians such as Liang Sicheng believed that the White Pagoda holds great significance, but they have not determined what exact significance the White Pagoda possessed (Steinhardt 1997, 54).</p>
                  -->
               </desc>
